      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Encounter at the Gas Pump: Other Views</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wendy Loveless letter on Peter Applebome's July 2 column on how to react to black man playing loud and offensive rap music at gas station pump holds tolerance is needed on both sides (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Dozens of readers responded to Peter Applebome's July 2 column. Here is a sampling of their reactions.</p>
        <p>What is it that truly bothers the father here, the fact that the person is playing offensive music so loud that he can physically feel it, or the fact that if he makes a request to turn down the music, he fears that it might become a racial incident?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Dozens of readers responded to Peter Applebome's July 2 column. Here is a sampling of their reactions.</p>
        <p>What is it that truly bothers the father here, the fact that the person is playing offensive music so loud that he can physically feel it, or the fact that if he makes a request to turn down the music, he fears that it might become a racial incident?</p>
        <p>I think both things would probably bother me, less the fact that the person is playing his offensive music so loudly than the fact that I might feel obliged to ignore the offense for fear of creating a racial incident.</p>
        <p>This is a problem that both blacks and whites have to address if there is to be racial harmony. There needs to be tolerance on both sides.</p>
        <p>WENDY LOVELESS  Millwood</p>
        <p>COUNTY LINES</p>
      </block>
